    narr:childCount "44"^^xsd:integer ;
    narr:generatedFrom "9ae2f624249375a3abbce1282b453198c1b97e9a" ;
    narr:narration """This hub collects friction and failure across four domains — AI-development loops, sales legibility, user adoption, and organizational memory — with enough cross-cutting tension that no single arc covers it.

On AI-development friction, [back-pressure from code volume](narr:Narrative_AIBackPressureCodeReview) was independently named by Scarlet and the customer's chief architect (Mar 2026): AI generates code faster than humans can review it, producing what Scarlet called 'eight honking PRs of world changing features.' The [action trap](narr:Narrative_AIActionTrap) compounds this: Tony diagnosed the mechanism where every AI response prompts another action and the answer is always yes, creating a loop with no natural exit (Apr 2026). The [framing-layer deflection](narr:Narrative_FramingLayerDeflection) pattern adds a third AI-pathology: LLM output that is cleaner and more decisive than warranted, generating procedural exit ramps.

Sales friction clusters around value legibility. [Understanding ≠ sale](narr:Obs_ScarletPurchaseTriggerQuote) is the core finding (Mar 2026); [two distinct purchase triggers](narr:Narrative_TwoPurchaseTriggers) map to solo professional and delegator pain moments. The [activation gap](narr:Narrative_ActivationGap) frames the product as positioned as an investment when it needs to behave as a tool, though [the deployment layer closing that gap](narr:Narrative_ActivationGapClosed) was confirmed by a design collaborator (Mar 2026). The [two-sided legibility problem](narr:Narrative_TwoSidedLegibilityProblem) extends this: patient illegibility and practitioner flattening are the same problem from opposite ends. A Jul 2026 child [inverts the felt/shown crux](narr:Narrative_ShowVsDemoProof): value is fully showable without the prospect's own data; their-own-data deepens conversion after value has already landed.

Adoption friction splits into technical and non-technical channels. [Contamination fear](narr:Narrative_TechnicalAdoptionFriction) — not product difficulty — blocks technically sophisticated users with existing AI workflows ([Tony's 10 repos](narr:Obs_TechnicalChaosQuote), [privacy concern](narr:Obs_PrivacyConcernQuote)). Non-technical onboarding gaps include [GitHub opacity](narr:Obs_OutsideTechBetaUserGitHubOpacityFeedback), [tool-language ambiguity post-install](narr:Obs_OutsideTechBetaUserToolLanguageFeedback), [identity grounding skipped as irrelevant](narr:Narrative_IdentityOnboardingGap), and [SMS trust tax in low-trust contexts](narr:Obs_OutsideTechBetaUserSMSSpamCodedQuote). The [multi-user repo system prompt challenge](narr:Narrative_MultiUserRepoPromptChallenge) surfaces a design tension specific to shared repos. The [staffing AI adoption wall](narr:Narrative_StaffingAIAdoptionWall) adds an organizational-conflict vector: AI that works too well can trigger internal friction that blocks adoption entirely.

Organizational memory failures form a fourth cluster. [Context hemorrhage](narr:Narrative_ContextHemorrhage) names the pattern of meetings run without structure, decisions made, minutes discarded (Jun 2026). The [forgetting bottleneck as a role](narr:Narrative_ForgettingBottleneckIsRole) is confirmed by two independent self-diagnoses from the customer's chief architect and an engineering manager at the customer (May 2026): the bottleneck is scarce memory at the decision junction, not scarce expertise. [Day-to-day re-litigation](narr:Narrative_DayToDayRelitigation) of options-vs-decisions is the recurring weekly manifestation, with [the ARB facilitator's verbatim](narr:Obs_OptionsVsDecisionsQuote) as the sharpest customer-language capture. The [scaling gap](narr:Narrative_ScalingGap) (McKinsey 2025: 78% use AI, only 33% scale it) situates the organizational memory failures in a broader adoption landscape.""" ;
    narr:covers <https://aswritten.ai/narrative#Narrative_AIActionTrap> ;
